review_blob: Surprise. This looks, tastes, and smells like the brewers used a Mexican Lager grain and hop bill. Its not to style but Im really enjoying it. Even more sessionable than its namesake.
beer_name: Full Sail Brewers Share Berliner Weiss

review_blob: Perfected IPA. What can you say. Super complex while being very accessible. Thank you Vinny! You have never done me wrong.
Very easy drinking ..... As a kolsch should be. No noticeable off flavors. Super clear with a nice straw color. Same price as Coors banquet on draft. Great choice for an all day drinker.

Pretty pretty barrel aged beer. Loads of presence without being overbearing. Malty in all of the right places, present yet yielding hops, nice touch of sour/"dill pickle" flavor in the finish. Smells of sea water when slightly warm.
Nice work. Slightly high gravity pilsner with a bit more viscosity than usually. Great brine and hop aroma with just a hint of pineapple in the finish. Right in between common and imperial pilsner.
Holy under attenuated. Super sweet. Nice hop notes after the sweetness subsides. The body is a bit weak. I can see where they are going with this. Let me know when they arrive.
All around bruiser. Loads of residual sweetness to balance out the buttload of hops. Big and herbal with a good amount of grapefruit backing it up. The bitterness lingers in the best kind of way.
Easy drinking unassuming IPA. Not to be passed as an option when selection is limited. The malt really shines.
Nice and hazy as unfiltered ale should be. Nice light body with a pleasantly mild hop aroma. Definitely East Coast IPA. Not bad not great. Inoffensive for sure.

Very mild and dry. The rye flavor against the hops is present yet unremarkable, which could be a good thing if one was looking for something sessionable with a touch more flavor than usual. The yeast character is whats tripping me up on this one. This is made for someone else.

Nice. Finding the balance in something seemingly unbalanced is quite fun. Huge syrupy apricot with a nice herbaceous follow up. This reminds me of what I love in the extremes of the IPA category. All of the malt, tons of hops but without the wallop.

The smoke is apparent but not overwhelming. The look over all is of dark cola minus the bubbles. Pretty straightforward compaired to some American contemporaries. Very close to Sprechers black lager with bit more malt.
Nice apple aroma and flavor. Nice nuttiness as well. A bit sweet, but to be expected for a high gravity "alt."
Unbeatable. Super consistent over the years.  I cant wait until its back. Im in love.
Nice floral bouquet. I.e. tons of jasmine in the nose. Nice balance considering. Just shy of sessionable.
Lightly sour, super dry, very effervescent. Pretty high in alcohol for a session beer at 4.5
Very nice across the board. A beautiful approach to balanced high gravity IPA. The malt really shines while acknowledging the low alpha hops.
